VALUES
(43, 3, 10, 40, 15, 14, 14, 'knowest not these things', 'Blindness of Spiritual Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness among leaders. In both passages, Jesus addresses the failure of those in authority to understand spiritual truths, leading to their downfall.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 10, 26, 36, 25, 27, NULL, 'Cleansing and New Heart Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual renewal and cleansing. Both passages emphasize the transformation of the heart and spirit, indicating a deeper understanding of spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 10, 5, 10, 16, 16, NULL, 'Heart and Understanding Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of inner transformation. Both passages emphasize the need for a change of heart and understanding, moving beyond mere external observance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 10, 5, 30, 6, 6, NULL, 'Heart and Understanding Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding and transformation of the heart. In John 3:10, Jesus questions the lack of understanding, while Deuteronomy 30:6 speaks of God circumcising the heart to enable love and life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 43, 8, 38, 38, 'testify that we have seen', 'Witness and Father Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of testimony and what is seen. In John 3:11, the speaker refers to their witness, while in John 8:38, the speaker contrasts their own experience with that of another father.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 43, 12, 49, 49, 'we speak that we do know', 'Witness and Commandment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in communication. Both passages emphasize the source of their messages, with John 3:11 referencing the witness of knowledge and John 12:49 indicating the commandment from the Father.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 62, 5, 6, 12, 'receive not our witness', 'Witness and Testimony Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of witness in both passages. John 3:11 speaks of receiving witness, while 1 John 5:9 emphasizes the greater witness of God regarding His Son.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 23, 65, 2, 2, 'receive not our witness', 'Rebellion and Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of divine testimony. John speaks of a people not receiving the witness, while Isaiah describes a rebellious people who do not follow good ways.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'receive not our witness', 'Witness and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in both passages. John 3:11 speaks of the rejection of witness, while 2 Corinthians 4:4 describes how the god of this world blinds the minds of those who believe not.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 23, 50, 2, 2, 'ye receive not our witness', 'Witness and Response to Call', 'This connection highlights the theme of unheeded testimony and calls for response. In John 3:11, the speaker notes that their witness is not received, paralleling Isaiah 50:2 where the speaker questions the lack of response to their call.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 11, 42, 10, 22, 22, 'ye receive not our witness', 'Knowledge of the Father and Son', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge and revelation. Both passages emphasize the relationship between the Father and the Son, indicating that true understanding comes through divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 46, 3, 1, 2, 'how shall ye believe, if I tell you of heavenly things?', 'Understanding Spiritual Maturity', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge of understanding deeper spiritual truths. John highlights the difficulty of believing heavenly things, while Paul addresses the Corinthians'' inability to grasp more profound teachings, indicating their spiritual immaturity.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 46, 2, 7, 9, 'how shall ye believe, if I tell you of heavenly things?', 'Connection of Wisdom and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding divine wisdom. Both passages emphasize the challenge of grasping heavenly truths and the mystery of God''s plans.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 58, 5, 11, 11, NULL, 'Understanding Spiritual Discernment', 'This connection highlights the challenge of understanding deeper spiritual truths. Both passages emphasize the difficulty of believing and comprehending profound concepts when one''s capacity to hear or understand is limited.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 43, 3, 31, 36, 'how shall ye believe, if I tell you of heavenly things?', 'Connection of Earthly and Heavenly', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between earthly and heavenly perspectives. John 3:12 introduces the challenge of believing earthly things, while John 3:31-36 contrasts those who are earthly with the one who comes from above.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 60, 2, 1, 3, NULL, 'Growth in Understanding Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual growth and understanding in both passages. John 3:12 emphasizes the need for belief in earthly things to grasp heavenly truths, while 1 Peter 2:1-3 encourages believers to desire the ''sincere milk of the word'' for growth.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 43, 1, 1, 14, 'how shall ye believe, if I tell you of heavenly things?', 'Connection of Belief and Light', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge of belief in divine truths. John 3:12 questions belief in heavenly things, while John 1:1-14 presents the Light that came into the world, which many did not recognize. This connection highlights the theme of understanding and accepting spiritual revelation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 12, 54, 3, 16, 16, 'believe not', 'Connection of Belief and Mystery', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in both passages. John 3:12 discusses the challenge of believing in heavenly things, while 1 Timothy 3:16 presents the mystery of godliness that requires belief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 20, 30, 4, 4, 'ascended up to heaven', 'Connection of Ascension and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ascension to heaven, questioning who has the authority to do so. John 3:13 directly states that no one has ascended except the Son of man, while Proverbs 30:4 poses a similar question about ascension and descent.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 43, 6, 38, 38, 'came down from heaven', 'Heavenly Origin of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' descent from heaven, highlighting his divine origin. John 3:13 states that no one has ascended to heaven except the Son of Man, while John 6:38 reiterates that he came down from heaven.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 44, 2, 34, 34, 'ascended up to heaven', 'Ascension and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension, where John 3:13 states that no one has ascended to heaven except the Son of Man, while Acts 2:34 emphasizes that David has not ascended into the heavens. Both passages underscore the unique authority of the Son of Man in relation to heavenly ascension.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 43, 1, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the unique role of the Son in revealing God. John 3:13 speaks of the Son''s descent from heaven, while John 1:18 highlights His declaration of the Father.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 46, 15, 47, 47, 'the Son of man which is in heaven', 'Connection of Heavenly Origins', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between earthly and heavenly beings. John 3:13 refers to the Son of man who came down from heaven, while 1 Corinthians 15:47 identifies the second man as the Lord from heaven.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 45, 10, 6, 6, 'ascended up to heaven', 'Connection of Ascension and Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension to heaven. Both passages address the concept of who can ascend, linking the idea of bringing Christ down from above.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 13, 49, 4, 9, 10, 'he that came down from heaven', 'Connection of Ascension and Descension', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension and descension in both passages. John 3:13 mentions the one who came down from heaven, while Ephesians 4:9-10 discusses the necessity of descending before ascending.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 14, 4, 21, 7, 9, 'lifted up', 'Connection of Healing and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation through looking upon the lifted object. Both passages emphasize that looking at the serpent on the pole leads to life, paralleling the necessity of looking to the Son of man for eternal life.', 'theme', 0.853, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 14, 43, 8, 28, 28, 'lifted up', 'Connection of ''lifted up''', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''lifted up'' in both passages, linking the act of Moses lifting the serpent to Jesus being lifted up. Both verses emphasize the significance of this action in revealing identity and purpose.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 14, 43, 12, 32, 34, 'lifted up', 'Connection of Being Lifted Up', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''lifted up,'' linking Moses'' serpent to Jesus'' crucifixion. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' death as a means of drawing people to Him.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 14, 42, 24, 26, 27, 'lifted up', 'Connection of Suffering and Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering leading to glory. Both passages emphasize the necessity of being ''lifted up'' and the fulfillment of scripture regarding Christ''s role.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 3, 14, 42, 24, 44, 46, 'must the Son of man be lifted up', 'Connection of Suffering and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of suffering for salvation. John 3:14 refers to the lifting up of the Son of man, paralleling Luke 24:46, which states that Christ must suffer and rise. This connection highlights the theme of salvation through suffering.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
